The '''A72 road''' is a major route in [[Scotland]] connecting [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]] in [[South Lanarkshire]], with [[Galashiels]] in the [[Scottish Borders]]. It travels for over {{Convert|60|mi|km|order=flip}} in a south-easterly direction, along the [[River Clyde|Clyde]] and [[River Tweed|Tweed]] valleys, passing the towns of [[Larkhall]], [[Lanark]], [[Biggar, South Lanarkshire|Biggar]] and [[Peebles]].

==Route==
===Hamilton to Lanark===
Starting at the junction with the [[A724 road (Great Britain)|A724]], the road parallels the [[M74 motorway|M74]], following the original A74 (now [[List of B roads in Great Britain|B7078]]) before descending into the forested [[Clyde Valley]] as it skirts around the town of Larkhall. The road follows the [[River Clyde]], with some tight bends, sheer drops and adverse cambers, and meets the [[A73 road|A73]] just north of Lanark. 

=== Lanark to Causewayend ===
This section of the road follows the course of the A73 through the town of Lanark and, just before [[Symington, South Lanarkshire|Symington]], again becomes the A72. It meets the main [[A702 road|A702]], [[Edinburgh]] to [[Abington, South Lanarkshire|Abington]], [[South Lanarkshire]] road; this short section of road is narrow as it passes through Symington.

=== Causewayend to Kaimrig End ===
[[File:The A72 At Wolfclyde - geograph.org.uk - 1077935.jpg|left|thumb|The A72 near Wolfclyde between [[Symington, South Lanarkshire|Symington]] and [[Biggar, South Lanarkshire|Biggar]]]]
This section of the road follows the course of the A702 for approximately 3 miles through the town of [[Biggar, South Lanarkshire|Biggar]]. The A72 enters the village of [[Skirling, Scottish Borders|Skirling]] before ascending onto higher moorland. This section of road is notorious for accidents due to its high elevation, poor weather and winding route.{{fact|date=April 2017}}

=== Kaimrig End to Galashiels ===
On this last {{Convert|6|mi|km|order=flip}} section of A72, it is the secondary route on the [[A701 road|A701]]. Just south of [[Blyth Bridge]], it meets the [[A721 road|A721]], and less than a mile further, it leaves the course of the A701. The A72 ascends a high plateau, then descends into the valley of the [[River Tweed]] at [[Stobo]], and parallels the Tweed for the remainder of its length.

The road passes through [[Peebles]] and then [[Innerleithen]] and [[Walkerburn]] towards Galashiels.  It comes to an end at a junction with the [[A7 road (Great Britain)|A7]], which leads on to the [[Galashiels]] Ring Road.

